## 1. WHAT APPLIES TO IN.TUNE ITSELF

This is the part people skip. You can't credibly assess someone else's control environment while your own is undocumented.

| Obligation | Why it bites you | Trigger |
|---|---|---|
| **FTC Safeguards Rule** (16 CFR 314) | You handle client financial data. If you're a "finding" or "servicing" entity for financial products, you're a *financial institution* under GLBA — the 2021 amendments swept in far more service providers than people expect. Requires named Qualified Individual, written risk assessment, encryption, MFA, incident response plan, annual board report. | Likely **already applies** |
| **FAR 52.204-21** | Basic safeguarding of Federal Contract Information. 15 controls. | Any federal contract |
| **NIST SP 800-171 / CMMC Level 2** | If you touch Controlled Unclassified Information. 110 controls, SPRS score posted, third-party assessment under CMMC. | CUI in scope |
| **CA/Browser Forum Baseline Requirements** + **WebTrust for RAs** | You're a GlobalSign RA. Your RA agreement almost certainly flows down BR §5 (management/operational controls), identity vetting procedures, and audit obligations. This is a real, examinable obligation. | **Already applies** |
| **AICPA independence / SSAE 18** | If you issue anything resembling an attestation report, you're in AT-C territory whether you meant to be or not. | Depends on report form |
| **State privacy** (TX DPSA, CCPA/CPRA if CA clients) | Texas Data Privacy and Security Act is live. | Threshold-based |
| **SOC 2 Type II** | Not law. But your clients' vendor risk teams will demand it, and you won't win regulated-entity work without one. | Market reality |

The RA obligation is the one I'd flag hardest. Being a Registration Authority means a CA has delegated identity vetting to you, and that delegation carries audit exposure. Most firms with an RA agreement don't fully internalize that.

